{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609995"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:57:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:57:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16142"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.04,0.08,0.55,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115210"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8833"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3618"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6694"},{"type":"tags","id":"9861"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21069"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115210"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the third trimester of pregnancy, the enlarged uterus can compress the inferior vena cava, particularly when a woman lies in the supine position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most significantly reduced by inferior vena cava compression during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uteroplacental blood flow","Maternal heart rate","Fetal heart rate","Maternal blood pressure","Amniotic fluid volume"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen the gravid uterus compresses the inferior vena cava, it reduces venous return to the heart. This leads to decreased cardiac output and reduced \u003Cstrong\u003Euteroplacental blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E, which can compromise fetal oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal heart rate\u003C/strong\u003E typically increases to compensate for reduced venous return. \u003Cstrong\u003EFetal heart rate\u003C/strong\u003E remains relatively stable unless there is significant compromise of uteroplacental circulation. \u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is maintained through compensatory mechanisms unless compression is severe. \u003Cstrong\u003EAmniotic fluid volume\u003C/strong\u003E is not directly affected by short-term changes in inferior vena cava compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is why pregnant women are advised to lie on their left side, which reduces compression of the inferior vena cava and maintains optimal uteroplacental circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Compression of the inferior vena cava by the gravid uterus in late pregnancy can reduce venous return and cardiac output.","Reduced cardiac output from inferior vena cava compression leads to decreased uteroplacental blood flow.","Supine position maximizes inferior vena cava compression, which is why left lateral positioning is recommended in late pregnancy."],"references":["Clark AR, Fontinha H, Thompson J, Couper S, Jani D, Mirjalili A, Bennet L, Stone P. Maternal Cardiovascular Responses to Position Change in Pregnancy. Biology (Basel). 2023 Sep 21;12(9):1268. doi: 10.3390/biology12091268. PMID: 37759669; PMCID: PMC10525953.","Soma-Pillay P, Nelson-Piercy C, Tolppanen H, Mebazaa A. Physiological changes in pregnancy. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2016 Mar-Apr;27(2):89-94. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2016-021. PMID: 27213856; PMCID: PMC4928162","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:02:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:04:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8833"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115210"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags